{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17645175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17645175"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:13:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18088"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18088"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.81,0,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10802"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59557"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5540"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25156"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25547"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUtilitarianism is an ethical framework that guides decision-making in healthcare.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the core principle of utilitarianism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Individual rights should never be violated","Actions should maximise benefit for the greatest number","Personal virtue determines right action","Decisions should follow absolute moral rules","Duties and obligations guide ethical choices"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe core principle of utilitarianism is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eactions should maximise benefit for the greatest number\u003C/strong\u003E of people. This ethical framework evaluates choices based on their consequences rather than predetermined rules or individual rights.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other ethical frameworks:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndividual rights should never be violated\u003C/strong\u003E represents deontological ethics, which focuses on inviolable rights rather than consequences\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPersonal virtue determines right action\u003C/strong\u003E represents virtue ethics, which emphasises character rather than consequences\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecisions should follow absolute moral rules\u003C/strong\u003E represents rule-based ethics, which conflicts with utilitarianism\u0027s focus on outcomes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuties and obligations guide ethical choices\u003C/strong\u003E represents duty-based ethics, which focuses on moral obligations rather than outcomes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn healthcare, utilitarian thinking helps guide resource allocation and public health decisions by considering what will produce the greatest good for the most people.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Utilitarianism evaluates the morality of actions based on their consequences and overall benefit to society.","The fundamental principle of utilitarianism is to maximise happiness or well-being for the greatest number of people.","Utilitarianism considers the outcomes of actions rather than the intentions behind them."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinica